Drift Naive¶

In [22]:
forecast = []
for i in range(12):
    forecast.append(0)
for i in range(len(test['Close']) - 12):
    if i%12==0:
        j=int(i/12)
    forecast.append(test['Close'][j*12+12]+(i%12)*(test['Close'][j*12+12]-test['Close'][j*12])/11)
test['DN_Close_Forecast'] = forecast
test.plot(x='Date',y=['Close','DN_Close_Forecast'], figsize=(30,10))
print(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test['Close'][12:] , test['DN_Close_Forecast'][12:])))

4.328502405566021

Weighted Average; 0.2,0.3,0.5¶

In [24]:
forecasts = []
for i in range(3):
    forecasts.append(0)
for i in range(len(test['Close'])-3):
    forecast = test['Close'][i]*0.2 + test['Close'][i+1]*0.2 + test['Close'][i+2]*0.5
    forecasts.append(forecast)
test['WA_Close_Forecast'] = forecasts
test.plot(x='Date',y=['Close','WA_Close_Forecast'], figsize=(30,10))

Single exponential smoothing¶

In [25]:
df1 = df.set_index('Date')
In [26]:
from statsmodels.tsa.api import SimpleExpSmoothing
from math import sqrt 


train1 = df1[(df1.index>'2009-01-01') & (df1.index<'2015-01-01')]
test1 = df1[(df1.index>'2015-01-01') & (df1.index<'2016-01-01')]
y_hat = test1.copy()

# fit a SES without specifying smooth parameter, so library does it for us
fitx = SimpleExpSmoothing(np.asarray(train1['Close'])).fit(optimized=True)
print('optimal alpha chosen:', fitx.model.params['smoothing_level'])

# fit a SES with explicitly supplied smooth parameter
fit2 = SimpleExpSmoothing(np.asarray(train1['Close'])).fit(smoothing_level=0.4, optimized=False)

# print the rmse of training step
rms_train_opt = sqrt(mean_squared_error(train1['Close'], fitx.fittedvalues)) 
print('rmse for fitted values with optimal alpha: ', rms_train_opt)
rms_train = sqrt(mean_squared_error(train1['Close'], fit2.fittedvalues)) 
print('rmse for fitted values with supplied alpha: ', rms_train)

# plot training data against fitted values using both models
plt.figure(figsize=(10,3))
plt.plot(fitx.fittedvalues, label = 'fitted opt')
plt.plot(fit2.fittedvalues, label = 'fitted')
plt.plot(train1['Close'], label='train')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.show()

optimal alpha chosen: 0.9489143577576017
rmse for fitted values with optimal alpha:  1.3220014390452282
rmse for fitted values with supplied alpha:  1.5750134328745318
In [27]:
# forecast using both models
y_hat['SES_opt_fcast'] = fitx.forecast(len(y_hat))
y_hat['SES_fcast'] = fit2.forecast(len(y_hat))

# plot the time series as train, test and forecasted
plt.figure(figsize=(10,3))
plt.plot(train1['Close'], label='train')
plt.plot(test1['Close'], label='test')
plt.plot(y_hat['SES_fcast'], label='SES_fcast')
plt.plot(y_hat['SES_opt_fcast'], label='SES_opt_fcast')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.show()

# calculate RMSE of the forecast on test data
rms = sqrt(mean_squared_error(test1.Close, y_hat.SES_fcast)) 
print('rmse for model with supplied alpha: ', rms)
rms_opt = sqrt(mean_squared_error(test1.Close, y_hat.SES_opt_fcast)) 
print('rmse for model with optimal alpha: ', rms_opt)

rmse for model with supplied alpha:  5.991921884228209
rmse for model with optimal alpha:  5.895209513001269

Dickey-Fuller¶

Null Hypothesis : TS is non stationarity¶

Alternate Hypothesis : TS is stationarity¶

If (ADF < critical value) ------> we reject null hypothesis

In [31]:
import statsmodels.tsa.stattools as ts
result = ts.adfuller(df['Close'])
print('ADF: ',result[0])
print('Critical Values:',result[4])

result = ts.adfuller(df['Diff_stationary'])
print('ADF: ',result[0])
print('Critical Values:',result[4])

ADF:  -2.1934921403028844
Critical Values: {'1%': -3.434179908502461, '5%': -2.863231689892687, '10%': -2.567670609760268}
ADF:  -19.656256736011866
Critical Values: {'1%': -3.434177666727206, '5%': -2.8632307003234203, '10%': -2.5676700828345895}

Non-stationarity for non transformed data¶

ADF > critical value -------> we donot reject null hypothesis

And hence, TS is non-stationarity

Hence, first order differencing was done and data has stationarity
